        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: route static scan findings through clawscan",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nThis centralizes static-scan enforcement behind ClawScan. Static scan results are still computed, persisted on versions/releases, and passed into the ClawScan prompt as structured evidence, but they no longer directly affect public moderation, installability, blocked malware flags, queue priority, or account autobans.\n\nThe user-visible audit experience now reflects that model: security audit pages, detail summaries, and the audits table no longer expose a separate Static analysis section or status lane. Public security snapshots are driven by ClawScan/LLM verdicts, with VirusTotal and SkillSpector retained as supporting scanner telemetry.\n\n## Root Cause\n\nStatic scan had grown from deterministic evidence into several enforcement paths: initial publish moderation, static update moderation, package trust status, public API security snapshots, queue prioritization, audit-page rendering, and autoban scheduling. That made static findings act like policy decisions even though ClawScan is now the intended adjudicator over static scan, VirusTotal, SkillSpector, and artifact context.\n\n## Changes\n\n- Store static scan findings as internal scan context only for skills and packages.\n- Remove static scan as a source of `blocked.malware`, public security verdicts, install blocks, queue priority, and autobans.\n- Schedule malware autobans only when ClawScan/LLM marks the latest skill version malicious.\n- Remove the public Static analysis section/status lane from security audit pages and audits list UI.\n- Update docs/specs so static findings are described as ClawScan input evidence, not a standalone public or enforcement verdict.\n- Update backend/API/UI tests around static-only findings, ClawScan malicious autobans, package trust, and audit rendering.\n\n## Validation\n\n- `bun run ci:static`\n- `bun run ci:unit`\n- `bun run ci:types-build`\n",
